  "prompt": "How electronic configuration is being done?",
  "response": "Electronic configuration refers to the distribution of electrons in the atomic orbitals of an atom. It follows specific rules based on quantum mechanics and the principles of electron arrangement. Here's how electronic configuration is determined:\n\n---\n\n### **Key Principles and Rules:**\n1. **Aufbau Principle:**  \n   Electrons fill atomic orbitals starting from the lowest energy level to higher energy levels. The order of filling is determined by the **n + l** rule, where:  \n   - **n** = principal quantum number (shell number),  \n   - **l** = azimuthal quantum number (orbital type: s=0, p=1, d=2, f=3).  \n   If two orbitals have the same **n + l** value, the one with the lower **n** is filled first.  \n\n   **Filling order (Madelung rule):**  \n   1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, 5s, 4d, 5p, 6s, 4f, 5d, 6p, 7s, 5f, 6d, 7p...\n\n2. **Pauli Exclusion Principle:**  \n   No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of quantum numbers. This means each orbital can hold a maximum of **2 electrons** with opposite spins (**\u2191\u2193**).\n\n3. **Hund's Rule:**  \n   When filling degenerate orbitals (orbitals with the same energy, e.g., 2p or 3d), electrons will occupy separate orbitals with parallel spins before pairing up. This minimizes electron repulsion.\n\n---\n\n### **Steps to Determine Electronic Configuration:**\n1. **Identify the Atomic Number (Z):**  \n   The atomic number equals the number of protons and electrons in a neutral atom.\n\n2. **Fill Orbitals in Order of Increasing Energy:**  \n   Use the **Aufbau principle** to fill orbitals from the lowest energy to the highest energy. For example:  \n   - Hydrogen (Z=1): 1s\u00b9  \n   - Carbon (Z=6): 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u00b2  \n   - Iron (Z=26): 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u2076  \n\n3. **Use Exceptions for Stability:**  \n   Some atoms (e.g., Cr, Cu) have exceptions to achieve greater stability (half-filled or fully filled d or f orbitals). For example:  \n   - Chromium (Z=24): [Ar] 4s\u00b9 3d\u2075 (instead of [Ar] 4s\u00b2 3d\u2074)  \n   - Copper (Z=29): [Ar] 4s\u00b9 3d\u00b9\u2070 (instead of [Ar] 4s\u00b2 3d\u2079)\n\n4. **Noble Gas Configuration (Short Form):**  \n   For convenience, the inner electron configuration is replaced by the noble gas symbol in brackets. For example:  \n   - Sodium (Z=11): [Ne] 3s\u00b9  \n   - Chlorine (Z=17): [Ne] 3s\u00b2 3p\u2075\n\n---\n\n### **Examples:**\n1. **Hydrogen (Z=1):**  \n   1s\u00b9  \n2. **Oxygen (Z=8):**  \n   1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2074  \n3. **Sodium (Z=11):**  \n   1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b9 or [Ne] 3s\u00b9  \n4. **Iron (Z=26):**  \n   1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u2076 or [Ar] 4s\u00b2 3d\u2076  \n5. **Copper (Z=29):**  \n   [Ar] 4s\u00b9 3d\u00b9\u2070  \n\n---\n\n### **Key Points to Remember:**\n- The **4s orbital** is filled before the **3d orbital**, but during ionization, 4s electrons are lost first.  \n- Half-filled (e.g., 3d\u2075) or fully filled (e.g., 3d\u00b9\u2070) orbitals are more stable due to symmetry and exchange energy.  \n- Electron configurations can be written in full or short notation using noble gas symbols.  \n\nBy following these rules, you can determine the electronic configuration of any atom!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
